1) What are various ways to add images in our App? Explain with code examples
Ans: There are several ways to import and use images in React. 
i)First way to add images in react is by adding them to source folder of your application.You can directly import image name from source file.
ex : import logo from './logo.svg'.
ii)Images in CSS  by using url(""). ex:.logo {
  background-image: url(./logo.png);
}
iii)Another way to import images that are stored in src folder is by using  require() function . In React require() function is avaliable thanks to node.js
ex: <img 
          src={require('./victor-grabarczyk-r02cXESP0aI-unsplash.jpg')} 
          alt="logo" 
        />
iv) Images through http . By adding image adreess in image src .
v) Local images
If you download the jpg images you should move it into the some testapp/src folder and import it as in first case.
vi)SVG as ReactComponent
If you are using React v16.3 or higher you can also import SVGs directly as React components.
Ex: import { ReactComponent as Logo } from './logo.svg'

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
       <Logo />  // React Component
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

vii)Binary data as base64 string.
Some times you might need to display an Image that is represented as a base64 string.
In that case, you may want to display the image as a jpeg like this:
function App() {

  const data = ''

  return (
    <div className="App">
        <img src={`data:image/jpeg;base64,${data}`} alt="secret"/>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

Conclusions
What is the best way to import images in React?

There is no right answer. Context matters. Moreover, it is possible that you will end up fetching images from a server rather than storing them in the app.

However, when this happens we can ask ourselves some questions:

Is the image going to be used in several places in the app? Probably, using the public folder is a better approach.
However, remember that none of the files in the public folder get post-processed or minified. Meaning you could end up with a pretty big bundle when you run npm run build. Overall, using the public folder should be the exception rather than the norm.

Is the image specific to a component? Probably, src/assets could be the right place. Furthermore, CRA “normally encourage(s) you to import assets in JavaScript files”.

4)What is SPA?
Ans: SPA stands for Single page Application. It is a web application that dynamically updates the webpage with data from web server 
with out reloading or refreshing entire page.Spa implementation that loads only a single web document, and then updates the body content of that single document.
5)What is difference between Client Side Routing and Server side routing?
In Server side routing every change in url http request is made to server to fetch the webpage and replace the current page   with newer webpage.
In client side routing during the first load the webapp is loaded from server to client after which when ever there is a change in url.
the router libray navigates to new page without sending any request to backend. All SPA uses Client-side routing.
